The paper discusses the design of a new pattern-matching-oriented programming language, which suggests that it belongs to the Programming Languages (cs.PL) sub-category. The paper specifically focuses on non-free data types, which are often represented as complex data structures such as multisets, sets, graphs, and symbolic mathematical expressions. This suggests that the paper may also belong to the Data Structures (cs.DS) sub-category. The paper also discusses the importance of efficiency, extensibility, and polymorphism in pattern matching, which suggests that it may belong to the Logic in Computer Science (cs.LO), Software Engineering (cs.SE), or Formal Languages and Automata Theory (cs.FL) sub-categories.
